":"Salford, Lancashire, England","Chorley, Cheshire, England":"Chorley, Cheshire, England","Great Harwood, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Chorley, Macclesfield, Cheshire, England, Britsh Isles":"Chorley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lacy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lassy in Calvados, named from a Gaulish personal name <i>Lascius</i> (of uncertain origin and meaning) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lasee","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English or Irish   Lacy  ."]},{"name":"Lacey","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Lacy  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Lacy was born in 1125, in Yorkshire, England as the daughter of Robert de Lacy. She had at least 4 sons with Richard de Fitton. She died about 1200, in Salford, Lancashire, England, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1125–about 1200":"1125–umbes 1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1120–1200":"1120–1200","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1099–1138":"1099–1138","about 1150":"umbes 1150","22 August 1138":"22. august 1138","1099":"1099","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","Abt 1152":"umbes 1152","1138":"1138","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","Abt 1154":"umbes 1154","1210":"1210","about 1200":"umbes 1200","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Great Harwood, Lancashire, England","Salford, Lancashire, England":"Salford, Lancashire, England","Chorley, Cheshire, England":"Chorley, Cheshire, England","Great Harwood, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Chorley, Macclesfield, Cheshire, England, Britsh Isles":"Chorley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1125–about 1200":"1125–noin 1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1120–1200":"1120–1200","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1152–Male":"1152–Kuollut","1154–Male":"1154–Kuollut","1099–1138":"1099–1138","about 1150":"noin 1150","22 August 1138":"22. elokuuta 1138","1099":"1099","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","Abt 1152":"noin 1152","1138":"1138","1125":"112